How's that?

Exotic orchard would be entirely dependent on your color pool and your opponents. That’s a meta thing.
meta can be studied and statistically figured out!
Locally?
Or at least roughly averaged out with enough repetitions
asking locally is a silly question on stats
Not when the locality is the most dependent factor
That is from the 4th seat by turn three, so in 300 games if you sat in the 4th seat in a 4 man pod 82% of the time Exotic Orchard was an ETB untapped tri-land
yeah, it should be run way more than it is
I always forget it’s a card
Obviously a small meta with a lot of mono decks would tweak that

The decks you play against skews the results. The more mono-colored decks you play against the less likely you are to get colors you need, and conversely the more 4-5 color decks you play against the more likely you are to get the colors you need. I probably should have tracked this variable but alas I did not.
Playing against green decks also would skew the results as land ramp provides more lands and thus more chances for those lands to produce colors you need.
The budget and power level of the decks you are facing also skews the results. A two color deck running mostly basics is going to have a lower percentage chance to provide your colors than is a variant on that same deck running fetches to get their ABUR dual or shock.
Given the fact that I'm extrapolating data out from one deck into 3 virtual decks it isn't as robust and diverse a data set as I'd get from doing 300 true games.
So what I’d do then, instead of showing the average, is show a spectrum from lowest odds (mono color) to highest with 4-5 color. The only consistent variable being 4 pod cause then that gets silly
So everyone can use the data
well, yeah
The amount of time to extrapolate out that many games would be insane
It's oen of those things where if you care about the details enough to read data on Exotic Orchard you can probably mentally determine yourself in your head how much of it applies to you
But yes, ideally I'd have full data sets for most possible variables
